  "unmapped_findings": [
    "Formation enthalpy and cohesive energy both increase monotonically with increasing Mn content across the Fe_{1-x}Mn_xAl series; FeAl (x=0) possesses the lowest formation enthalpy (-0.391 eV·atom^{-1}) and is the most thermodynamically stable alloy.",
    "Chemical bonding analysis indicates that all Fe-Mn-Al alloys exhibit a combination of covalent and metallic bonds, leading to predicted good electronic conductivity, high melting points and high hardness.",
    "Brittle-to-ductile behavior predicted: FeAl and Fe_{0.875}Mn_{0.125}Al are brittle (B/G = 1.56 and 1.75, respectively), while all other compositions with higher Mn content are ductile (B/G > 1.75).",
    "MnAl exhibits the strongest elastic anisotropy among the studied alloys (universal anisotropic index A^U = 3.80), whereas FeAl is the most isotropic (A^U = 0.56).",
    "Fe_{0.5}Mn_{0.5}Al shows anomalous extrema including the lowest Young's modulus (202.1 GPa), lowest shear modulus (77.2 GPa), lowest Debye temperature (533.3 K), and highest Poisson's ratio (0.309) and B/G ratio (2.28), indicating the highest ductility and compressibility among the intermediate compounds.",
    "Figure 9 illustrates planar projections of Young's modulus on (001) and (110) crystallographic planes showing strong directional dependence and disparate anisotropy; detailed numerical angular dependencies are not provided in the text."
